00:04:19.250 --> 00:04:20.560
from the atomic physics side.

00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:36.550
So in perturbation theory, we
have a mixture of other states.

00:04:36.550 --> 00:04:41.725
And this said mixture is
done with the matrix element.

00:04:47.110 --> 00:04:49.650
And in perturbation
theory, we always

00:04:49.650 --> 00:04:52.430
have an energy denominator.

00:04:52.430 --> 00:04:55.510
Intermediate state
to ground state.

00:04:55.510 --> 00:04:59.740
And if the electric field
is smaller than this value,

00:04:59.740 --> 00:05:04.880
then we have mixture of other
states into the ground state.

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:07.850
So usually when we estimate
the validity of perturbation

00:05:07.850 --> 00:05:15.590
theory, we look
for the state which

00:05:15.590 --> 00:05:17.270
is closest to the ground state.

00:05:17.270 --> 00:05:20.320
For which the energy
denominator is smallest.

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:27.510
So therefore, i here is the
nearest state, but, and this

00:05:27.510 --> 00:05:29.090
is important, of
opposite parity.

00:05:35.410 --> 00:05:40.060
Otherwise, because of the
parity selection rule,

00:05:40.060 --> 00:05:42.672
the matrix element would
be 0 and electric field

00:05:42.672 --> 00:05:44.460
does nothing.

00:05:44.460 --> 00:05:47.685
I made a comment on Friday,
but let me do it again.

00:05:47.685 --> 00:05:50.800
That, of course, means that
when we apply electric field

00:05:50.800 --> 00:05:52.890
to our favorite
atoms, we don't have

00:05:52.890 --> 00:05:57.660
to worry about the
other hyperfine states.

00:05:57.660 --> 00:06:00.840
The other hyperfine states have
the same spatial wave function.

00:06:00.840 --> 00:06:02.260
Have the same parity.

00:06:02.260 --> 00:06:05.770
So we are really here talking
about the first excited state.

00:06:05.770 --> 00:06:07.630
And a concrete example
for those of you

00:06:07.630 --> 00:06:11.420
who work with alkalis
with an s ground

00:06:11.420 --> 00:06:13.930
state, the relevant
energy scale here

00:06:13.930 --> 00:06:18.460
is the excitation energy
to the first p state.

00:06:18.460 --> 00:06:25.910
So let's just estimate it
for a single electron atom.

00:06:25.910 --> 00:06:34.220
And well, this is a
hydrogenic estimate.

00:06:34.220 --> 00:06:44.890
The excitation energy to
the first excited state.

00:06:44.890 --> 00:06:48.610
1s to 2p is about 1 Rydberg.

00:06:48.610 --> 00:06:51.170
And the Rydberg is
nothing, or Hartree,

00:06:51.170 --> 00:06:54.720
and that's nothing else
than e square over a0.

00:06:54.720 --> 00:06:57.800
It's electric potential
of two charges separated

00:06:57.800 --> 00:07:00.160
by Bohr radius.

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:08.560
And if we estimate
that the matrix element

00:07:08.560 --> 00:07:12.830
for strong transition is on
the order of the Bohr radius,

00:07:12.830 --> 00:07:15.330
there are no other length
scales in the problem,

00:07:15.330 --> 00:07:20.750
we find that the value for the
electric field in atomic units

00:07:20.750 --> 00:07:25.990
is the charge divided by
the Bohr radius squared.

00:07:25.990 --> 00:07:28.070
And this is really high.

00:07:28.070 --> 00:07:36.350
It is on the order of 5 times
10 to the 9 volt per centimeter.

00:07:36.350 --> 00:07:47.190
And this is 1,000 times
larger than laboratory

00:07:47.190 --> 00:07:48.100
electric fields.

00:07:56.130 --> 00:07:59.400
Those fields would just create
sparking along the electrodes.

00:07:59.400 --> 00:08:01.820
You cannot apply such
high electric fields

00:08:01.820 --> 00:08:03.390
in a laboratory.

00:08:03.390 --> 00:08:05.020
So, therefore, nothing
to worry about.

00:08:05.020 --> 00:08:07.670
If you have ground state
atoms, the Stark effect

00:08:07.670 --> 00:08:10.974
in perturbation theory
is all you need.

00:08:10.974 --> 00:08:12.890
Actually, to be a little
bit more precise when

00:08:12.890 --> 00:08:18.740
I used the Rydberg and a0, I
made a little bit overestimate.

00:08:18.740 --> 00:08:21.820
So that the typically the
critical electric field

00:08:21.820 --> 00:08:25.050
which would cause a breakdown
of perturbation theory

00:08:25.050 --> 00:08:28.590
for the ground
state is around 10

00:08:28.590 --> 00:08:31.780
to the 9 volt per centimeter.

00:08:31.780 --> 00:08:38.340
OK, so we are safe when we
talk about ground states.

00:08:38.340 --> 00:08:43.830
But once we got to the excited
state, we have degeneracy.

00:08:43.830 --> 00:08:46.320
p states have a
three fold degeneracy

00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:48.720
and they are states
with opposite parity.

00:08:48.720 --> 00:08:50.450
So we can't have mixing there.

00:08:50.450 --> 00:08:54.670
And actually as we will
see for excited states,

00:08:54.670 --> 00:08:57.420
we have already a breakdown
of perturbation theory

00:08:57.420 --> 00:09:00.050
at very, very small
electric field.

00:09:02.660 --> 00:09:06.380
So let us discuss
hydrogenic orbits

00:09:06.380 --> 00:09:10.180
with principal
quantum number, n.

00:09:10.180 --> 00:09:17.810
And if you estimate what is
the size of the matrix element?

00:09:17.810 --> 00:09:20.040
Well, it's not just a0.

00:09:20.040 --> 00:09:24.140
There is a scaling with
n which is n square.

00:09:24.140 --> 00:09:28.210
The matrix element in higher
and higher excited state scales

00:09:28.210 --> 00:09:28.990
with n square.

00:09:33.150 --> 00:09:37.230
Well, how does the
energy separation scale?

00:09:37.230 --> 00:09:39.530
Well, let's not
discuss hydrogen here.

00:09:39.530 --> 00:09:42.074
Because in hydrogen, energy
levels are degenerate.

00:09:42.074 --> 00:09:43.740
And we would immediately
get a breakdown

00:09:43.740 --> 00:09:45.500
of perturbation theory.

00:09:45.500 --> 00:09:49.810
Let's rather formulate
it for general atoms.

00:09:49.810 --> 00:09:56.200
And we had this nice discussion
about the quantum defect.

00:09:56.200 --> 00:10:05.587
So if we compare the energy of
two l states, they scale as 1

00:10:05.587 --> 00:10:06.170
over n square.

00:10:09.780 --> 00:10:22.500
But for different l states, we
have different quantum defects.

00:10:22.500 --> 00:10:24.860
Delta l plus 1.

00:10:24.860 --> 00:10:26.520
And here we have delta l.

00:10:31.770 --> 00:10:35.420
So, therefore, doing
an expansion in m

00:10:35.420 --> 00:10:40.820
which we assume to be large, we
find that the energy difference

00:10:40.820 --> 00:10:46.920
is proportional to the
difference between the quantum

00:10:46.920 --> 00:10:48.480
defects for the
two states we want

00:10:48.480 --> 00:10:51.490
to mix with the electric field.

00:10:51.490 --> 00:10:56.360
And then again, the scaling with
the principal quantum number

00:10:56.360 --> 00:10:57.270
is n cube.

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:06.470
So, therefore, we find
for the critical field

00:11:06.470 --> 00:11:10.240
using the criterion
I mentioned above.

00:11:10.240 --> 00:11:12.060
We take the energy splitting.

00:11:12.060 --> 00:11:17.420
The energy the denominator which
appears in perturbation theory.

00:11:17.420 --> 00:11:21.895
We divide by the value
of the matrix element.

00:11:25.590 --> 00:11:36.940
Well, we had the Rydberg
constant or two times

00:11:36.940 --> 00:11:45.150
the Rydberg constant is nothing
else than b squared over a0.

00:11:45.150 --> 00:11:49.190
The matrix element
was 1 over a0.

00:11:49.190 --> 00:11:56.280
And then we have the difference
between quantum defects.

00:11:56.280 --> 00:11:59.310
And now-- and this makes
it really so dramatic.

00:11:59.310 --> 00:12:02.730
We had an n square scaling
of the matrix element.

00:12:02.730 --> 00:12:06.970
And we have an into the minus 3
scaling of energy differences.

00:12:06.970 --> 00:12:13.560
So that means the critical
field scales by n to the 5.

00:12:13.560 --> 00:12:16.920
Go to an excited state
with n equals 10.

00:12:16.920 --> 00:12:18.665
And the breakdown of
perturbation theory

00:12:18.665 --> 00:12:22.110
happens 100,000 times earlier.

00:12:22.110 --> 00:12:25.280
So some of the scaling
in atomic physics

00:12:25.280 --> 00:12:27.365
is very, very
dramatic when you go

00:12:27.365 --> 00:12:29.540
to more highly excited state.

00:12:32.370 --> 00:12:44.650
If you threw in that quantum
defects become very small,

00:12:44.650 --> 00:12:47.810
once you go beyond
s and p states.

00:12:47.810 --> 00:12:51.260
The higher states just don't
penetrate into the nucleus.

00:12:51.260 --> 00:12:58.010
So if l is larger than 2, if
you have more complicated atoms,

00:12:58.010 --> 00:13:01.740
you may add the angular
momentum of the core here.

00:13:01.740 --> 00:13:05.490
But so if you put n to the 5
scaling and the small quantum

00:13:05.490 --> 00:13:10.780
defect together, you find
that critical electric fields

00:13:10.780 --> 00:13:16.490
are smaller than one
volt per centimeter

00:13:16.490 --> 00:13:22.340
already for principal
quantum numbers as low as 7.

00:13:22.340 --> 00:13:28.610
So that means bring a 1.5 volt
battery close to your atom

00:13:28.610 --> 00:13:30.080
and you drive it crazy.

00:13:30.080 --> 00:13:31.835
You drive it out of
perturbation theory.

00:13:36.810 --> 00:13:39.790
So what we have
is the following.

00:13:39.790 --> 00:13:41.620
We have, of course,
the structure

00:13:41.620 --> 00:13:43.120
of atoms in excited field.

00:13:43.120 --> 00:13:45.910
Here is the electric field.

00:13:45.910 --> 00:13:50.810
And let me just
pick three n values.

00:13:50.810 --> 00:13:53.660
18, 19, 20.

00:13:53.660 --> 00:13:56.500
And now the
structure, of course,

00:13:56.500 --> 00:14:04.630
is that by the
criterion I actually

00:14:04.630 --> 00:14:07.740
gave you was the criterion for
the application of perturbation

00:14:07.740 --> 00:14:08.790
theory.

00:14:08.790 --> 00:14:13.640
If the energy levels are
smaller than the matrix element,

00:14:13.640 --> 00:14:16.940
you have to rediagonalize
between those levels.

00:14:16.940 --> 00:14:20.710
And that gives you then not a
quadratic, but a linear effect.

00:14:20.710 --> 00:14:23.160
So, therefore, the
structure is here

00:14:23.160 --> 00:14:31.071
that you have a region where
you have strong l mixing.

00:14:31.071 --> 00:14:32.820
So you have to use
degenerate perturbation

00:14:32.820 --> 00:14:35.550
theory for the
different l states.

00:14:35.550 --> 00:14:40.450
But the many folds in n, the
principle quantum number,

00:14:40.450 --> 00:14:43.640
are still well separated.

00:14:43.640 --> 00:14:49.100
But then, eventually,
when you go further,

00:14:49.100 --> 00:14:53.100
you have a region which
is called n mixing.

00:14:53.100 --> 00:14:55.150
So now the electric
field is really

00:14:55.150 --> 00:14:58.900
completely rediagonalizing your
states with different quantum

00:14:58.900 --> 00:14:59.710
numbers, n.

00:15:04.450 --> 00:15:07.500
So the result of
this discussion is

00:15:07.500 --> 00:15:12.210
that highly excited
states of atoms

00:15:12.210 --> 00:15:15.985
behave very differently
from ground state atoms.

00:15:15.985 --> 00:15:18.880
And n to the 5 scaling
is sensitivity to volt

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:20.070
per centimeter.

00:15:20.070 --> 00:15:22.680
Level mixing all over the place.

00:15:22.680 --> 00:15:28.530
And that's why for those
highly excited states,

00:15:28.530 --> 00:15:32.730
people have coined the word
Rydberg atoms or Rydberg

00:15:32.730 --> 00:15:33.440
matter.

00:15:33.440 --> 00:15:36.930
That means atoms with higher
principal quantum numbers.

00:15:36.930 --> 00:15:45.310
And the study of Rydberg
atoms was pioneered, well,

00:15:45.310 --> 00:15:49.610
the early pioneering work
by our own, Dan Kleppner.

00:15:49.610 --> 00:15:54.370
And then Herbert
Walther in Munich

00:15:54.370 --> 00:15:57.900
who happened to be
my Ph.D. Advisor.

00:15:57.900 --> 00:16:01.330
And finally, Serge
Haroche, who was recognized

00:16:01.330 --> 00:16:04.510
with the last Nobel Prize
together with Dave Wineland.

00:16:10.160 --> 00:16:13.020
So this is not just theory.

00:16:13.020 --> 00:16:21.600
What I am showing to
you here is spectroscopy

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:24.410
done at MIT by Dan Kleppner.

00:16:24.410 --> 00:16:27.990
So what is done here is
from the ground state,

00:16:27.990 --> 00:16:31.970
they excite to an excited state.

00:16:31.970 --> 00:16:37.400
And whenever you hit an excited
state, you see a signal.

00:16:37.400 --> 00:16:43.250
Let's focus on the upper part.

00:16:46.020 --> 00:16:49.980
So if at a given electric
field, you scan the laser,

00:16:49.980 --> 00:16:51.520
you get one of those traces.

00:16:51.520 --> 00:16:54.640
You find peaks, peaks, peaks.

00:16:54.640 --> 00:16:58.510
And those peaks correspond to
the different and many folds

00:16:58.510 --> 00:17:00.880
with strong Stark mixing.

00:17:00.880 --> 00:17:03.860
And eventually when you go
to somewhat higher field,

00:17:03.860 --> 00:17:05.980
you have states
all over the place.

00:17:05.980 --> 00:17:10.130
And this is the regime where
you have done n mixing.

00:17:10.130 --> 00:17:13.640
So in the '70s and
'80s, there was really,

00:17:13.640 --> 00:17:16.859
those experiments obtained
a clear understanding

00:17:16.859 --> 00:17:20.680
and description
of atoms in, well,

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:22.400
I would say high
electric fields.

00:17:22.400 --> 00:17:23.900
But the fields were not so high.

00:17:23.900 --> 00:17:26.185
It was just the atoms were
very sensitive that already

00:17:26.185 --> 00:17:27.560
is at lower electric
fields, they

00:17:27.560 --> 00:17:29.920
reached what is regarded
as the high-field limit.

00:17:34.790 --> 00:17:39.990
Now the question is
when we recorded signal,

00:17:39.990 --> 00:17:42.930
suddenly the traces stop.

00:17:42.930 --> 00:17:46.520
And that means the electric
field is now so high

00:17:46.520 --> 00:17:49.980
that the atom no longer
has a stable state.

00:17:49.980 --> 00:17:52.860
The electric field is so
high that it literally rips

00:17:52.860 --> 00:17:55.740
the electron away from the atom.

00:17:55.740 --> 00:17:59.580
And if you go to higher
states, the electric field

00:17:59.580 --> 00:18:01.900
where this happens is lower.

00:18:01.900 --> 00:18:04.440
This is the process
of field ionization

00:18:04.440 --> 00:18:07.891
and that's what we
want to discuss next.

