Dan Kleppner is the
person who tried

00:18:19.940 --> 00:18:22.570
to do almost all
experiments with hydrogen.

00:18:22.570 --> 00:18:24.630
The famous BEC experiment.

00:18:24.630 --> 00:18:27.820
He also had the
Rydberg experiment

00:18:27.820 --> 00:18:31.125
which was just in building 26
where Vladan Vuletic teaches

00:18:31.125 --> 00:18:33.110
now, his labs.

00:18:33.110 --> 00:18:34.780
This is where
spectroscopy of hydrogen

00:18:34.780 --> 00:18:37.120
were done with the
goal of a precision

00:18:37.120 --> 00:18:39.440
measurement of the
Rydberg constant.

00:18:39.440 --> 00:18:42.700
So we excited hydrogen to
some of those high levels.

00:18:42.700 --> 00:18:45.900
But as probably
the experts know,

00:18:45.900 --> 00:18:50.080
the hydrogen atom is the
hardest atom to work with.

00:18:50.080 --> 00:18:52.790
Because you need
[INAUDIBLE] and alpha.

00:18:52.790 --> 00:18:56.280
You have this huge gap to
the first excited state.

00:18:56.280 --> 00:18:58.180
And that's why if
you can get away,

00:18:58.180 --> 00:19:00.090
you try to work
with other atoms.

00:19:00.090 --> 00:19:02.615
And in those
experiments, those people

00:19:02.615 --> 00:19:04.710
worked with the lithium atom.

00:19:04.710 --> 00:19:07.760
So the lithium atom
has a quantum defect

00:19:07.760 --> 00:19:10.710
which will actually contrast
to hydrogen where the quantum

00:19:10.710 --> 00:19:11.900
defect is 0.

00:19:11.900 --> 00:19:14.450
And this will actually
be very, very important

00:19:14.450 --> 00:19:18.334
for field ionization as
I want to discuss now.

00:19:18.334 --> 00:19:19.000
Other questions?

00:19:23.280 --> 00:19:30.720
OK, so at a given electric
field, states, so to speak,

00:19:30.720 --> 00:19:32.580
just disappear.

00:19:32.580 --> 00:19:34.720
They're no longer stable.

00:19:34.720 --> 00:19:37.583
And this is the process which
is called field ionization.

00:19:49.450 --> 00:19:56.990
So the phenomenon is
that sufficiently strong

00:19:56.990 --> 00:20:03.950
electric fields ionize the atom.

00:20:08.420 --> 00:20:11.150
And whenever there
is a simple model

00:20:11.150 --> 00:20:15.270
and I can give you an analytic
answer, I try to do that.

00:20:15.270 --> 00:20:17.690
Because I feel a
lot of our intuition

00:20:17.690 --> 00:20:20.760
is shaped by understanding
simple models.

00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:24.370
And the simplest model
for field ionization

00:20:24.370 --> 00:20:27.520
is just the classical
model by calculating

00:20:27.520 --> 00:20:31.570
what is the settle point
in the combined potential.

00:20:31.570 --> 00:20:33.550
The combined potential
of the nucleus

00:20:33.550 --> 00:20:38.320
which is a Coulomb potential
and the external magnetic field.

00:20:38.320 --> 00:20:40.880
So many features
of the experiment

00:20:40.880 --> 00:20:43.880
can be understood by this
simple three line derivation.

00:20:46.460 --> 00:20:48.920
So we have a potential.

00:20:48.920 --> 00:20:56.240
One part of it is the
Coulomb potential.

00:20:56.240 --> 00:20:59.620
And focusing on one
spatial direction here.

00:20:59.620 --> 00:21:09.655
And then, in addition, we
apply an electric field.

00:21:13.460 --> 00:21:16.785
And the electric field
creates a linear potential.

00:21:19.360 --> 00:21:24.970
And if I take the sum of the
two, well, at large distances,

00:21:24.970 --> 00:21:27.860
see, it's the electric
field which dominates.

00:21:27.860 --> 00:21:30.320
Then the Coulomb
potential takes over.

00:21:33.350 --> 00:21:35.800
So that's how it looks like.

00:21:35.800 --> 00:21:42.190
So now we have the situation
if we would put in atoms

00:21:42.190 --> 00:21:45.620
and we would look at
the energy eigenvalues.

00:21:45.620 --> 00:21:52.100
At this point, this is
the maximum excited state

00:21:52.100 --> 00:21:54.800
in the atom which
is still stable.

00:21:54.800 --> 00:21:58.400
So what I want to derive
for you is what determines

00:21:58.400 --> 00:22:01.630
the stability is simply
the settle point.

00:22:01.630 --> 00:22:06.170
When the binding energy of
the excited state for which we

00:22:06.170 --> 00:22:09.990
use the Rydberg
formula is not stronger

00:22:09.990 --> 00:22:12.680
than the position
of the settle point,

00:22:12.680 --> 00:22:17.140
the atom becomes unstable it
and becomes field ionized.

00:22:17.140 --> 00:22:18.900
And we'll discuss
a little bit later

00:22:18.900 --> 00:22:21.510
if this really
applies to real atoms.

00:22:21.510 --> 00:22:25.820
The quick answer is for lithium
and all the other atoms,

00:22:25.820 --> 00:22:26.810
it applies.

00:22:26.810 --> 00:22:28.630
For hydrogen, it doesn't.

00:22:28.630 --> 00:22:30.624
Because hydrogen has
too many symmetries.

00:22:30.624 --> 00:22:31.790
Too many exact degeneracies.

00:22:34.730 --> 00:22:46.050
OK, so the total potential
is the Coulomb potential

00:22:46.050 --> 00:22:49.396
plus the electric potential.

00:22:56.250 --> 00:23:02.210
What we need is the position
of the settle point.

00:23:02.210 --> 00:23:07.200
Where we have a
maximum in this one.

00:23:07.200 --> 00:23:08.570
This is a one dimensional cut.

00:23:08.570 --> 00:23:12.810
And this one dimensional cut
has a maximum at this position.

00:23:12.810 --> 00:23:16.610
And by taking the derivative
of the total potential,

00:23:16.610 --> 00:23:21.530
you immediately find
this to be of that value.

00:23:21.530 --> 00:23:25.490
And now what we are
calculating next

00:23:25.490 --> 00:23:30.455
is what is the potential
energy at this point.

00:23:33.260 --> 00:23:42.160
And, well, this is just copy
from the notes, e to the 3/2.

00:23:45.020 --> 00:23:47.140
And now what we want
to do is we want

00:23:47.140 --> 00:23:51.290
to postulate that
for field ionization,

00:23:51.290 --> 00:23:56.970
this should be able to the
binding energy of the electron.

00:23:56.970 --> 00:24:01.620
Which is nothing
else than the Rydberg

00:24:01.620 --> 00:24:03.160
constant divided by n square.

00:24:10.900 --> 00:24:14.160
OK, now here, we
have the square root

00:24:14.160 --> 00:24:20.140
of the electric field
from this calculation.

00:24:20.140 --> 00:24:25.530
So that means the critical
electric field will scale as 1

00:24:25.530 --> 00:24:26.690
over n to the 4.

00:24:29.740 --> 00:24:32.930
And this is a
famous scaling which

00:24:32.930 --> 00:24:35.900
can be found in many textbooks.

00:24:35.900 --> 00:24:43.070
That the critical electric
field for ionization equals,

00:24:43.070 --> 00:24:45.080
and now, that's the
beauty of atomic units,

00:24:45.080 --> 00:24:50.090
it is 1/16, n to the 4.

00:24:50.090 --> 00:24:54.670
Beautiful formula derived from
the settle point criteria.

00:24:54.670 --> 00:24:58.070
Of course, what I mean here is,
and if you do the derivation,

00:24:58.070 --> 00:24:59.215
it's in atomic units.

00:25:03.130 --> 00:25:08.460
Which means in units
of the atomic unit

00:25:08.460 --> 00:25:12.390
of the electric field which is
e over the Bohr radius squared.

00:25:19.250 --> 00:25:21.650
So it's a simple model.

00:25:21.650 --> 00:25:23.150
It's an analytic result.

00:25:23.150 --> 00:25:25.980
The question is is it valid?

00:25:25.980 --> 00:25:27.560
Does it make any sense?

00:25:27.560 --> 00:25:33.579
And the answer is yes, but in
a quantum mechanical problem,

00:25:33.579 --> 00:25:35.620
you would actually solve
Schroedinger's equation,

00:25:35.620 --> 00:25:36.750
such a potential.

00:25:36.750 --> 00:25:39.510
But then, the onset
of field ionization

00:25:39.510 --> 00:25:44.060
comes when tunnelling becomes
possible for this barrier.

00:25:44.060 --> 00:25:46.510
But it is the
nature of tunnelling

00:25:46.510 --> 00:25:50.190
that if you're a little bit too
low, tunneling is negligible.

00:25:50.190 --> 00:25:53.730
You may have ionization rates
of 1 per millisecond or so.

00:25:53.730 --> 00:25:55.880
And if you just go
a little bit closer,

00:25:55.880 --> 00:25:58.710
it becomes exponentially larger.

00:25:58.710 --> 00:26:01.750
So, therefore, this scaling
is very, very accurate.

00:26:01.750 --> 00:26:04.630
Because the transition where
you go from weak tunneling,

00:26:04.630 --> 00:26:07.470
to strong tunneling, to
spilling over the barrier,

00:26:07.470 --> 00:26:09.530
it's a very narrow range
of electric fields.

00:26:13.520 --> 00:26:16.460
But, yes, people have looked
at it in great details

00:26:16.460 --> 00:26:24.220
and have calculated
corrections due to tunneling.

00:26:24.220 --> 00:26:29.890
So these are quantum corrections
to the classical threshold

00:26:29.890 --> 00:26:30.890
which I just calculated.

00:26:39.120 --> 00:27:02.370
But now in hydrogen, a lot of
n, l mixing matrix elements,

00:27:02.370 --> 00:27:05.000
matrix elements due
to the electric field

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:07.910
between an l states vanish.

00:27:07.910 --> 00:27:13.990
Hydrogen is just too
pure, too precise.

00:27:13.990 --> 00:27:16.670
There is actually
parabolic quantum numbers

00:27:16.670 --> 00:27:18.330
where you can
exactly diagonalize

00:27:18.330 --> 00:27:20.040
hydrogen electric fields.

00:27:20.040 --> 00:27:23.860
And you find some stable
states which do not decay.

00:27:23.860 --> 00:27:26.360
And they are above the
classical threshold

00:27:26.360 --> 00:27:31.840
we have just calculated.

00:27:31.840 --> 00:27:35.440
So as Dan Kleppner would have
said, the simplest of all atoms

00:27:35.440 --> 00:27:39.050
is the most complicated when
it comes to field ionization.

00:27:39.050 --> 00:27:46.670
Because it has a
lot of stable states

00:27:46.670 --> 00:27:47.940
above the classical barrier.

00:28:01.550 --> 00:28:05.410
So you can sort of
envision that there

00:28:05.410 --> 00:28:09.060
will be orbits which are
just confined to this region.

00:28:09.060 --> 00:28:13.180
And the electron never
samples the settle point.

00:28:13.180 --> 00:28:19.210
And if you look at it
this diagram on the wiki,

00:28:19.210 --> 00:28:21.930
these are actually
calculations for hydrogen

00:28:21.930 --> 00:28:24.740
which include ionization rates.

00:28:24.740 --> 00:28:27.680
You will find that
the states which

00:28:27.680 --> 00:28:30.600
are the ones which
go down, which

00:28:30.600 --> 00:28:33.730
are on the downhill side
of the electric field,

00:28:33.730 --> 00:28:38.870
you see always here marked
an onset for ionization.

00:28:38.870 --> 00:28:40.980
And then you see
a rapid increase

00:28:40.980 --> 00:28:42.610
in the ionization rate.

00:28:42.610 --> 00:28:45.160
But you also see
those hydrogenic state

00:28:45.160 --> 00:28:49.590
which go upward in energy
and they refuse to ionize.

00:28:49.590 --> 00:28:52.410
Because of the symmetry
of parabolic coordinates

00:28:52.410 --> 00:28:55.190
and the things I've mentioned.

00:28:55.190 --> 00:28:58.020
Anyway, it's too especially
to spend more time here

00:28:58.020 --> 00:29:02.590
in class on it, but I just
think you should at least know

00:29:02.590 --> 00:29:07.890
qualitatively what is
different for hydrogen.

00:29:11.870 --> 00:29:14.170
OK, so that's what
I wanted to tell you

00:29:14.170 --> 00:29:21.220
about high electric fields and
field ionization in principle.

00:29:21.220 --> 00:29:25.820
Let me now briefly mention
important applications

00:29:25.820 --> 00:29:27.700
of field ionization.

00:29:39.440 --> 00:29:55.070
One is close to 100% detection
efficiency for atoms.

00:29:55.070 --> 00:29:57.680
If you want to
detect single atoms,

00:29:57.680 --> 00:30:00.500
for instance, you'll
have a krypton sample

00:30:00.500 --> 00:30:03.950
and you want to find a
rare isotope of krypton

00:30:03.950 --> 00:30:06.720
for dating the material.

00:30:06.720 --> 00:30:08.710
You need an extremely
high sensitivity

00:30:08.710 --> 00:30:12.000
and you may just have a few
single atoms in the sample.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:19.680
One way to do it would be
that you excite the atom maybe

00:30:19.680 --> 00:30:22.640
through an intermediate
state, to Rydberg state.

00:30:30.210 --> 00:30:33.380
And then by just applying
a few volt per centimeter,

00:30:33.380 --> 00:30:34.460
you get an ion.

00:30:34.460 --> 00:30:38.380
And ions can be counted
by particle detectors.

00:30:38.380 --> 00:30:41.320
You can accelerate the ion,
smash it into a surface

00:30:41.320 --> 00:30:46.390
and count the particles with
close to 100% efficiency.

00:30:46.390 --> 00:30:51.130
And this is one of the most
sensitive detection schemes.

00:30:51.130 --> 00:30:54.680
I remember in the
aftermath of Chernobyl,

00:30:54.680 --> 00:30:56.890
there was an interest
in detection schemes

00:30:56.890 --> 00:30:58.180
for radioactive strontium.

00:30:58.180 --> 00:31:00.450
And on the wiki, I
give you a reference

00:31:00.450 --> 00:31:04.070
where some people developed
this resonance ionization

00:31:04.070 --> 00:31:07.480
spectroscopy for
some atomic isotopes.

00:31:07.480 --> 00:31:10.760
Which unfortunately
appeared more frequently

00:31:10.760 --> 00:31:13.030
after the Chernobyl disaster.

00:31:13.030 --> 00:31:15.700
And they developed
a method based

00:31:15.700 --> 00:31:18.180
on excitation to Rydberg states.

00:31:18.180 --> 00:31:21.020
Which was more sensitive
than other methods.

00:31:21.020 --> 00:31:25.295
You may ask why don't you
ionize it with a laser?

00:31:25.295 --> 00:31:28.930
Well, the fact is, you can
photoionize it with a laser.

00:31:28.930 --> 00:31:32.460
It's another alternative, but
it takes much more laser power.

00:31:32.460 --> 00:31:34.880
Because if you excite
into the continuum,

00:31:34.880 --> 00:31:37.090
the matrix element
is much smaller.

00:31:37.090 --> 00:31:40.710
And often, if you want to have
100% ionization probability

00:31:40.710 --> 00:31:45.170
to go into the continuum, you
need such high laser power

00:31:45.170 --> 00:31:49.750
that you may get some background
of resonant ionization

00:31:49.750 --> 00:31:52.160
of other elements and such.

00:31:52.160 --> 00:31:54.760
So Rydberg atoms is really
the smart way to go.

00:31:54.760 --> 00:31:59.280
You go to an almost bound to
an almost unbound electron.

00:31:59.280 --> 00:32:01.170
And then it's just
the electric field

00:32:01.170 --> 00:32:06.655
which causes the final
act of ionization.

00:32:11.590 --> 00:32:17.710
I also want to briefly mention
that the famous experiments

00:32:17.710 --> 00:32:22.380
on Rydberg atoms by
Herbert Walther and Serge

00:32:22.380 --> 00:32:27.520
Haroche and collaborators
would not have been possible

00:32:27.520 --> 00:32:28.690
without field ionization.

00:32:31.990 --> 00:32:38.370
I give you this one
reference, but I'm

00:32:38.370 --> 00:32:42.160
sure you'll find more
in the actually very,

00:32:42.160 --> 00:32:44.910
very nicely written Nobel
lecture of Serge Haroche.

00:32:44.910 --> 00:32:47.300
I just read it a few
weeks ago and it's

00:32:47.300 --> 00:32:51.480
a delight to read how
he exposes the field.

00:32:51.480 --> 00:32:58.690
So they did QED experiments by
having microwave transitions

00:32:58.690 --> 00:33:02.020
between atoms in two
highly excited states.

00:33:02.020 --> 00:33:05.640
Let's say with principal
quantum number 50 and 51.

00:33:05.640 --> 00:33:10.320
So that's now conveniently
in the microwave regime.

00:33:10.320 --> 00:33:21.070
Then those atoms are
passed through a cavity.

00:33:21.070 --> 00:33:26.410
And in this cavity, single atoms
interact with single photons.

00:33:26.410 --> 00:33:29.840
And they have done beautiful
quantum non-demolition

00:33:29.840 --> 00:33:31.440
experiments of single photons.

00:33:31.440 --> 00:33:37.830
I mean that's really wonderful,
state of the art experiments.

00:33:37.830 --> 00:33:40.430
Back to Rydberg atoms
and field ionization.

00:33:40.430 --> 00:33:42.740
Eventually, the read
out of those experiments

00:33:42.740 --> 00:33:46.570
was you prepare atoms
in the state 50 or 51.

00:33:46.570 --> 00:33:49.600
And afterwards, if they have
absorbed or emitted a photon,

00:33:49.600 --> 00:33:51.640
they should be in
a different state.

00:33:51.640 --> 00:33:55.500
So you were interested in a very
high detection efficiency which

00:33:55.500 --> 00:33:59.660
could distinguish
between 50 and 51.

00:33:59.660 --> 00:34:03.950
And of course there is a
way to distinguish that.

00:34:03.950 --> 00:34:07.230
And this is because
of n to the 4.

00:34:07.230 --> 00:34:09.400
You first apply
an electric field

00:34:09.400 --> 00:34:12.810
which can only field ionized 51.

00:34:12.810 --> 00:34:14.750
And then you allow
the atoms to propagate

00:34:14.750 --> 00:34:17.239
into a slightly
higher electric field.

00:34:17.239 --> 00:34:19.850
And then the 50s are ionized.

00:34:19.850 --> 00:34:23.530
So the standard
experiment is that you

00:34:23.530 --> 00:34:29.065
pass those atoms between
two field plates.

00:34:31.889 --> 00:34:39.920
And by putting an angle
between them that indicates

00:34:39.920 --> 00:34:43.469
the voltage is increasing.

00:34:43.469 --> 00:34:47.390
And then you have
two little holes.

00:34:47.390 --> 00:34:52.310
You have some channel-drawn
particle detectors.

00:34:52.310 --> 00:34:59.200
And the first detector
will detect the 51s

00:34:59.200 --> 00:35:02.850
and the second detector will
detect the lower lying states.

00:35:02.850 --> 00:35:06.690
So you can detect every
atom with high probability,

00:35:06.690 --> 00:35:09.300
but also in a state
selective way.

00:35:15.590 --> 00:35:21.930
So this way of doing state
selective field ionization

00:35:21.930 --> 00:35:25.370
based on the discussion
we had earlier, this

00:35:25.370 --> 00:35:29.590
is sort of the method of
choice for experiments

00:35:29.590 --> 00:35:31.080
involving Rydberg atoms.

00:35:36.960 --> 00:35:41.680
Any questions about atoms
in the electric fields?

00:35:48.230 --> 00:35:50.320
Well, then.

00:35:54.650 --> 00:35:59.010
Frequently we add
time dependence.

00:35:59.010 --> 00:36:03.690
So what we should
do next is atoms

00:36:03.690 --> 00:36:07.790
in oscillating electric fields.

00:36:07.790 --> 00:36:10.320
It's also a good way to
review what we have done.

00:36:10.320 --> 00:36:12.190
Because the first
thing to do now

00:36:12.190 --> 00:36:16.160
is we calculate the
polarizability for AC fields.

00:36:16.160 --> 00:36:18.360
We calculate the
AC Stark effect.

00:36:18.360 --> 00:36:21.830
And, of course, if in the AC
Stark effect we said omega 2, 0

00:36:21.830 --> 00:36:24.260
will retrieve the
DC Stark effect.

00:36:24.260 --> 00:36:26.460
So in a way, what I'm
doing for you now is

00:36:26.460 --> 00:36:29.010
I'm using time dependent
perturbation theory

00:36:29.010 --> 00:36:30.680
to obtain a new result.

00:36:30.680 --> 00:36:33.400
But it will reproduce
the result of time

00:36:33.400 --> 00:36:38.250
independent perturbation theory
which we have just discussed.

00:36:38.250 --> 00:36:48.450
All right, so atoms in
oscillating electric fields.

00:36:56.490 --> 00:36:58.330
Of course the next
step is, and this

00:36:58.330 --> 00:37:00.490
is where we are
working towards, we

00:37:00.490 --> 00:37:04.214
will in the next few lectures
starting on Wednesday.

00:37:04.214 --> 00:37:06.630
Well, then there is Spring
Break, but in the next lectures

00:37:06.630 --> 00:37:09.140
develop a deep
understanding what

00:37:09.140 --> 00:37:12.120
happens when atoms
interact with light.

00:37:12.120 --> 00:37:14.800
And oscillating electric
fields is already

00:37:14.800 --> 00:37:16.230
pretty close to light.

00:37:16.230 --> 00:37:17.760
And I want to
actually also show you

00:37:17.760 --> 00:37:21.830
that we capture already a
lot of the phenomena which

00:37:21.830 --> 00:37:25.175
happen with light except
for a full understanding

00:37:25.175 --> 00:37:28.220
of spontaneous emission.

00:37:28.220 --> 00:37:32.170
So we pretty much when we use
an oscillating electric field,

00:37:32.170 --> 00:37:35.310
we allow the atom to
interact with just one

00:37:35.310 --> 00:37:37.310
mode of the
electromagnetic field.

00:37:37.310 --> 00:37:39.740
Which is filled with
a coherent state.

00:37:39.740 --> 00:37:41.580
And this is so classical
that we don't even

00:37:41.580 --> 00:37:42.760
need field quantization.

00:37:42.760 --> 00:37:45.050
We just use a classical
electric field.

00:37:45.050 --> 00:37:49.570
And this already gives us the
interaction of atoms with light

00:37:49.570 --> 00:37:51.570
except for spontaneous
emission which

00:37:51.570 --> 00:37:53.810
involves all the other modes.

00:37:53.810 --> 00:37:55.790
So that's what we do later.

00:37:55.790 --> 00:37:59.300
But today, we just do the
same classical description

00:37:59.300 --> 00:38:03.680
of an atom in an
oscillating electric field.

00:38:03.680 --> 00:38:09.120
And this is the theory
of the AC Stark effect.

00:38:09.120 --> 00:38:14.650
So all we do is application
of time dependent perturbation

00:38:14.650 --> 00:38:15.150
theory.

00:38:22.530 --> 00:38:25.546
So our electric field
is now time dependent.

00:38:28.070 --> 00:38:32.740
It has a value epsilon,
polarization e hat,

00:38:32.740 --> 00:38:33.490
and it oscillates.

00:38:36.390 --> 00:38:41.120
Our perturbation
Hamiltonian is exactly

00:38:41.120 --> 00:38:45.890
the same dipole Hamiltonian
we had before for the DC Stark

00:38:45.890 --> 00:38:47.220
effect.

00:38:47.220 --> 00:38:49.170
But now it's a
time dependent one.

00:38:52.940 --> 00:39:03.430
And it will be useful to break
up the oscillating term in e

00:39:03.430 --> 00:39:06.740
to the i omega, t and e
to the minus i omega t.

00:39:10.670 --> 00:39:14.320
I don't want to bore you with
perturbation theory in quantum

00:39:14.320 --> 00:39:21.570
mechanics because you've
all seen it in 805 or 806.

00:39:21.570 --> 00:39:23.570
I just want to
jump to the result.

00:39:23.570 --> 00:39:26.120
You find more details
about it on the wiki.

00:39:26.120 --> 00:39:30.530
But all you do is you
parametrize your wave function,

00:39:30.530 --> 00:39:35.560
you expand it into
eigenstates with amplitude an.

00:39:41.130 --> 00:39:44.820
And then you put it into
the Schroedinger equation

00:39:44.820 --> 00:39:51.140
and assume that for
short times the atom

00:39:51.140 --> 00:39:52.260
is in the ground state.

00:39:52.260 --> 00:39:54.700
The amplitude of the
ground state is 1.

00:39:54.700 --> 00:39:57.150
And the amplitude
of the excited state

00:39:57.150 --> 00:39:59.810
is infinitesimal that you
can use the lowest order

00:39:59.810 --> 00:40:02.240
perturbation.

00:40:02.240 --> 00:40:05.720
This immediately gives
you the first order result

00:40:05.720 --> 00:40:10.150
for the amplitude in
an excited state, k.

00:40:10.150 --> 00:40:13.870
It only comes about because
your initial state, the ground

00:40:13.870 --> 00:40:20.760
state, is coupled by the matrix
element to the excited state.

00:40:20.760 --> 00:40:23.190
It's linear in the
applied electric field.

00:40:26.590 --> 00:40:29.750
So what you do is you have
the Schroedinger equation

00:40:29.750 --> 00:40:33.410
and you integrate it
from times 0 to time 1.

00:40:33.410 --> 00:40:39.490
And since you have e
to the i omega, t and e

00:40:39.490 --> 00:40:47.460
to the minus i omega t, you
get two time dependent terms.

00:40:47.460 --> 00:40:48.080
e to the i.

00:40:53.140 --> 00:40:59.850
So what appears now is we
have the frequencies omega

00:40:59.850 --> 00:41:02.990
n of the excited state.

00:41:02.990 --> 00:41:09.690
And now when we couple
the excited state, k,

00:41:09.690 --> 00:41:11.620
to the ground
state, what appears

00:41:11.620 --> 00:41:14.160
is the frequency
difference between the two.

00:41:14.160 --> 00:41:18.650
That's pretty much
the excitation gap.

00:41:18.650 --> 00:41:24.360
And we have a time dependent
oscillation at omega.

00:41:24.360 --> 00:41:29.160
And then we have, of
course, the same term

00:41:29.160 --> 00:41:32.810
where we flip the
sign from omega--

00:41:32.810 --> 00:41:34.120
let me write that more clearly.

00:41:34.120 --> 00:41:44.210
Where we flip the sign
from omega to minus omega.

00:41:44.210 --> 00:41:45.390
So that's the second term.

00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:54.880
By integrating an exponential
function with respect to time,

00:41:54.880 --> 00:42:00.150
we get an energy and a frequency
denominator which is this one.

00:42:00.150 --> 00:42:02.710
So this is really
just straight forward,

00:42:02.710 --> 00:42:05.310
most basic plain
vanilla application

00:42:05.310 --> 00:42:07.082
of perturbation theory.

00:42:07.082 --> 00:42:09.290
The only thing I want to
discuss because it sometimes

00:42:09.290 --> 00:42:12.940
confuses people is
that we integrate

00:42:12.940 --> 00:42:16.550
from times 0 to the finite time.

00:42:16.550 --> 00:42:21.450
And then you integrate,
you get contributions

00:42:21.450 --> 00:42:23.280
from the upper
integration limit.

00:42:23.280 --> 00:42:28.000
And from the lower
integration limit.

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:35.650
And this contribution at
the lower integration limit

00:42:35.650 --> 00:42:40.950
is actually a transient.

00:42:40.950 --> 00:42:43.090
It is at the frequency.

00:42:49.530 --> 00:42:51.410
It doesn't depend on omega.

00:42:51.410 --> 00:42:54.590
So it's a beat node between
the ground and excited state.

00:42:54.590 --> 00:42:56.650
I could say at
frequency omega k,

00:42:56.650 --> 00:43:01.020
but then it's together with the
ground state, it's omega kg.

00:43:01.020 --> 00:43:06.450
And this is due to if you
switch on a perturbation,

00:43:06.450 --> 00:43:08.390
it's like you suddenly
switch on the drive

00:43:08.390 --> 00:43:09.580
of an harmonic oscillator.

00:43:09.580 --> 00:43:10.940
And you have some ringing.

00:43:10.940 --> 00:43:16.216
You have a transient at
the natural frequency

00:43:16.216 --> 00:43:17.340
of the harmonic oscillator.

00:43:17.340 --> 00:43:18.780
It has nothing to
do with the drive.

00:43:18.780 --> 00:43:19.835
It's just a sudden onset.

00:43:22.650 --> 00:43:27.320
It's transient and frequent
due to the sudden switch on.

00:43:31.410 --> 00:43:33.580
So like any
transient, we haven't

00:43:33.580 --> 00:43:34.742
included damping in here.

00:43:34.742 --> 00:43:36.200
We don't have
spontaneous emission.

00:43:36.200 --> 00:43:37.240
Everything is undamped.

00:43:37.240 --> 00:43:40.640
But eventually, all
those transients

00:43:40.640 --> 00:43:43.560
will damp out with time.

00:43:43.560 --> 00:43:46.360
And as we should have known
also from the beginning,

00:43:46.360 --> 00:43:50.890
when we drive a system, when
we switch on a perturbation,

00:43:50.890 --> 00:43:52.670
just think about an
harmonic oscillator.

00:43:52.670 --> 00:43:55.460
You have a response at the
harmonic oscillator frequency

00:43:55.460 --> 00:43:57.520
which is always
transient in nature.

00:43:57.520 --> 00:44:00.650
And then you have a response
at the dry frequency.

00:44:00.650 --> 00:44:02.520
And we are
interested, of course,

00:44:02.520 --> 00:44:14.760
only in the driven response
The driven response

00:44:14.760 --> 00:44:17.610
is at frequency
plus minus omega.

00:44:17.610 --> 00:44:19.290
That's how we drive it.

00:44:19.290 --> 00:44:21.380
But now I have to
be careful since I'm

00:44:21.380 --> 00:44:27.050
looking at the amplitude and I
factor out the time dependence

00:44:27.050 --> 00:44:32.540
of the time dependence of
the wave function, the time

00:44:32.540 --> 00:44:34.560
dependence of the eigenstates.

00:44:34.560 --> 00:44:38.240
I'm now looking for drive
terms in this expression

00:44:38.240 --> 00:44:41.940
for the amplitude which
are at frequency omega,

00:44:41.940 --> 00:44:50.570
but modified by the ground.

00:44:50.570 --> 00:44:52.760
Or the frequency of
the ground state.

00:44:52.760 --> 00:44:55.180
But anyway, what I mean
is the relevant term

00:44:55.180 --> 00:44:57.330
is the one which
depends on omega.

00:44:57.330 --> 00:45:01.230
And in the following discussion,
I simply drop the minus 1

00:45:01.230 --> 00:45:02.740
because it's a transient.

00:45:02.740 --> 00:45:06.440
If you would switch on your
time dependent electric field

00:45:06.440 --> 00:45:08.715
in a smoother way, this
term would disappear.

00:45:13.100 --> 00:45:16.750
OK, let's now be specific.

00:45:16.750 --> 00:45:21.540
Let's assume the electric field
points in the z direction.

00:45:21.540 --> 00:45:33.670
For an isotropic medium,
the dipole moment,

00:45:33.670 --> 00:45:37.406
the time dependent dipole
moment which we induce

00:45:37.406 --> 00:45:42.660
is also pointing
in the z direction.

00:45:42.660 --> 00:45:48.940
And so we want to calculate now
what is the dipole moment which

00:45:48.940 --> 00:45:53.610
is created by the drive term?

00:45:53.610 --> 00:45:58.610
By the driven electric Field

00:45:58.610 --> 00:46:04.940
And for that, we simply
use the perturbation theory

00:46:04.940 --> 00:46:06.820
we have just applied.

00:46:06.820 --> 00:46:12.640
We take the ground state and
its first order correction.

00:46:12.640 --> 00:46:16.445
And calculate the expectation
value of the dipole moment.

00:46:20.220 --> 00:46:23.820
In the line at the top, we
have the first order correction

00:46:23.820 --> 00:46:26.850
to the ground state
wave function.

00:46:26.850 --> 00:46:29.600
And so we just plug it in.

00:46:29.600 --> 00:46:34.330
And what we obtain
is result where

00:46:34.330 --> 00:46:39.930
we have the matrix
elements squared.

00:46:39.930 --> 00:46:42.270
Remember, we do first
order perturbation theory

00:46:42.270 --> 00:46:44.660
which is one occurrence
of the matrix element,

00:46:44.660 --> 00:46:46.640
but now we take a
second matrix element

00:46:46.640 --> 00:46:49.550
because we're interested
in the dipole operator.

00:46:49.550 --> 00:46:54.085
So this gives us now a sum
over matrix element squared.

00:46:57.450 --> 00:47:01.890
We have e to the plus i omega
t and e to the minus i omega t.

00:47:01.890 --> 00:47:04.905
This means we get 2 times the
real part of this expression.

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:13.890
And the time dependent
term is e to the i omega t.

00:47:20.130 --> 00:47:23.900
And then we have the term
with plus and minus omega.

00:47:27.941 --> 00:47:28.440
Yes.

00:47:35.400 --> 00:47:38.530
And so, most
importantly, everything

00:47:38.530 --> 00:47:40.340
is driven by the electric field.

00:47:49.340 --> 00:47:57.500
We can now just to write
the result in an easier way,

00:47:57.500 --> 00:48:01.420
we can use this result
with omega minus omega.

00:48:01.420 --> 00:48:07.840
And the real part
and write that.

00:48:07.840 --> 00:48:13.980
We can write that as
2 times omega k, g.

00:48:13.980 --> 00:48:23.720
Omega k, g squared minus omega
squared, times cosine omega t,

00:48:23.720 --> 00:48:26.500
times the electric field.

00:48:26.500 --> 00:48:30.410
And now finally, we
have the matrix element.

00:48:30.410 --> 00:48:37.020
We have integrated the e to the
i omega t function and such.

00:48:37.020 --> 00:48:41.350
So what we have here now is the
time dependent electric field.

00:48:41.350 --> 00:48:45.710
And what we have
here is the factor

00:48:45.710 --> 00:48:48.510
by which we multiply
the electric field

00:48:48.510 --> 00:48:50.550
to obtain the bipole moment.

00:48:50.550 --> 00:48:52.820
And this is the
definition of the now

00:48:52.820 --> 00:48:55.260
time dependent or frequency
dependent polarizability.

00:48:59.260 --> 00:49:00.260
AUDIENCE: Excuse me.

00:49:00.260 --> 00:49:01.012
PROFESSOR: Yes?

00:49:01.012 --> 00:49:03.964
AUDIENCE: Why are we only
getting the cosine and not

00:49:03.964 --> 00:49:05.440
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:49:05.440 --> 00:49:11.836
You only multiply by the other
terms to get the [INAUDIBLE]?

00:49:15.280 --> 00:49:16.756
In terms of the cosine.

00:49:21.347 --> 00:49:23.180
PROFESSOR: I haven't
done the math yesterday

00:49:23.180 --> 00:49:24.740
when I prepared for the class.

00:49:24.740 --> 00:49:27.530
I did it a while ago
when I wrote those notes,

00:49:27.530 --> 00:49:36.370
but you know, one comment, I
know you don't want to hear it,

00:49:36.370 --> 00:49:37.650
but it's a following.

00:49:37.650 --> 00:49:40.010
This system has no
dissipation at all.

00:49:40.010 --> 00:49:42.490
And when I drive
it, I will always

00:49:42.490 --> 00:49:48.740
get a response which is
in phase with the drive.

00:49:48.740 --> 00:49:51.030
It can be cosine omega t,
or minus cosine omega t.

00:49:51.030 --> 00:49:53.120
You cannot get a
quadrature at this point.

00:49:53.120 --> 00:49:57.350
So if you find I've made a
mistake, and you would say,

00:49:57.350 --> 00:49:59.900
there is a sine, omega
term, I've made a mistake.

00:49:59.900 --> 00:50:03.220
I know for physical reasons,
I cannot get a phase shift.

00:50:03.220 --> 00:50:06.180
You only get a phase shift
in the response of a system

00:50:06.180 --> 00:50:08.956
to drive when you
have dissipation.

00:50:08.956 --> 00:50:10.980
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:50:10.980 --> 00:50:12.864
I'll have to talk with you.

00:50:12.864 --> 00:50:14.280
PROFESSOR: But why
don't-- I mean,

00:50:14.280 --> 00:50:15.990
I know the result is correct.

00:50:15.990 --> 00:50:18.360
And this is just, I
hate to spend class time

00:50:18.360 --> 00:50:23.000
in trying to figure out
if I've omitted one term.

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:24.000
AUDIENCE: The real part.

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:28.772
PROFESSOR: But the real part
what I've probably done is--

00:50:28.772 --> 00:50:30.730
AUDIENCE: I think that's
probably what you did.

00:50:30.730 --> 00:50:31.229
Yeah.

00:50:31.229 --> 00:50:32.689
Thank you.

00:50:32.689 --> 00:50:34.230
PROFESSOR: I think
that's what I did.

00:50:34.230 --> 00:50:37.460
So let me, therefore,
also say we have now

00:50:37.460 --> 00:50:40.520
included the real part of it.

00:50:40.520 --> 00:50:41.040
Yes.

00:50:41.040 --> 00:50:43.240
OK, thank you.

00:50:43.240 --> 00:50:56.760
OK, this part here
can actually--

00:50:56.760 --> 00:50:58.190
that's how we often report.

00:50:58.190 --> 00:51:01.340
And that's how you often
find in textbook the result,

00:51:01.340 --> 00:51:04.920
the frequency dependence
of the AC polarizability.

00:51:04.920 --> 00:51:19.470
But I like to rewrite it
now in a different way which

00:51:19.470 --> 00:51:20.915
is identical.

00:51:23.880 --> 00:51:31.340
And it shows now that there
are two contributions.

00:51:31.340 --> 00:51:40.680
And I will discuss
them in a moment.

00:51:40.680 --> 00:51:46.725
But those two contributions,
one has in the denominator,

00:51:46.725 --> 00:51:50.080
let's assume we excite the
system close to resonance.

00:51:50.080 --> 00:51:52.200
Omega is close to omega kg.

00:51:52.200 --> 00:51:54.720
Then one term is
much, much closer.

00:51:54.720 --> 00:51:57.980
It's to a near
resonant excitation.

00:51:57.980 --> 00:52:01.040
And from our discussion
about rotating frames,

00:52:01.040 --> 00:52:05.100
we have all of this near
resonant excitation corresponds

00:52:05.100 --> 00:52:08.310
to a corotating term.

00:52:08.310 --> 00:52:11.134
And the other one corresponds
to a counter rotating term.

00:52:14.850 --> 00:52:16.770
We've not assumed any
rotating fields here,

00:52:16.770 --> 00:52:21.000
but we find those terms with
the same mathematical signature.

00:52:21.000 --> 00:52:23.520
And I will discuss
that little bit later.

00:52:23.520 --> 00:52:27.570
But the physics is between the
corotating and counterrotating

00:52:27.570 --> 00:52:28.070
term.

00:52:28.070 --> 00:52:35.190
And it's the
corotating term which

00:52:35.190 --> 00:52:37.799
is the term which [INAUDIBLE]
the so-called rotating

00:52:37.799 --> 00:52:38.590
wave approximation.

00:52:42.590 --> 00:52:45.050
I just want to identify
those two terms

00:52:45.050 --> 00:52:50.720
and let's hold the thought for
until we have the discussion.

00:52:50.720 --> 00:52:55.740
What I first want to say
is the limiting case.

00:52:55.740 --> 00:52:59.630
We have not made any
assumptions about frequency.

00:52:59.630 --> 00:53:07.380
When we let omega go to 0,
we obtain the DC result.

00:53:12.310 --> 00:53:14.900
It is important to point
out that when we have the DC

00:53:14.900 --> 00:53:19.170
result, we can only get to
correct results because we have

00:53:19.170 --> 00:53:25.720
equal contributions from co
and counterrotating terms.

00:53:33.380 --> 00:53:37.650
So that's sort of a
question one could ask.

00:53:37.650 --> 00:53:40.850
You know, which mistake do you
do for the DC polarizability

00:53:40.850 --> 00:53:43.740
when you do the rotating
wave approximation?

00:53:43.740 --> 00:53:46.300
Well, you miss out
on exactly 50% of it.

00:53:46.300 --> 00:53:48.215
Because both terms
become equally important.

00:53:52.350 --> 00:53:58.750
I have deliberately focused
here on the calculation

00:53:58.750 --> 00:54:01.380
of the dipole moment.

00:54:01.380 --> 00:54:05.640
Because the dipole, I simply
calculated the dipole moment

00:54:05.640 --> 00:54:08.150
as being proportion
to the electric field.

00:54:08.150 --> 00:54:13.570
And the coefficient in front of
it is alpha the polarizability.

00:54:13.570 --> 00:54:18.260
You may remember that
when we calculated

00:54:18.260 --> 00:54:20.490
the effect of a
static electric field,

00:54:20.490 --> 00:54:25.480
we looked for the DC Stark shift
for the shift of energy levels.

00:54:25.480 --> 00:54:30.125
We can now discuss also
the AC Stark shift.

00:54:33.750 --> 00:54:39.890
Which is a shift of the
energy levels due to the time

00:54:39.890 --> 00:54:41.220
dependent field.

00:54:41.220 --> 00:54:43.880
But I have to say you have
to be a little bit careful.

00:54:43.880 --> 00:54:46.700
And sometimes when I looked
at equations like this,

00:54:46.700 --> 00:54:49.250
there is a moment of confusion
what you want to actually,

00:54:49.250 --> 00:54:50.890
what the question is.

00:54:50.890 --> 00:54:53.980
Because the wave function is now
a time dependent wave function.

00:54:53.980 --> 00:54:55.420
It's a driven system.

00:54:55.420 --> 00:54:57.705
It's no longer your time
independent Schroedinger

00:54:57.705 --> 00:54:59.550
equation and you
are asked, what is

00:54:59.550 --> 00:55:02.210
the shift in the
value of eigenvalues?

00:55:02.210 --> 00:55:05.700
So the AC Stark
shift here is now

00:55:05.700 --> 00:55:10.710
given by the frequency
dependent polarizability.

00:55:10.710 --> 00:55:14.540
And then, and I know some
textbooks do it right away.

00:55:14.540 --> 00:55:17.520
And at the end of the
day, it may confuse you.

00:55:17.520 --> 00:55:21.390
It uses an average of e square.

00:55:21.390 --> 00:55:24.060
So in other words, if you
have an electric field which

00:55:24.060 --> 00:55:29.390
is cosine omega t, and you
calculate what is the AC Stark

00:55:29.390 --> 00:55:32.930
shift, you get
another factor of 1/2.

00:55:32.930 --> 00:55:37.700
Because cosine square omega
t time average is 1/2.

00:55:37.700 --> 00:55:41.190
So anyway, just
think about that.

00:55:41.190 --> 00:55:44.237
It's one of those factors
of 1/2 which is confusing.

00:55:44.237 --> 00:55:45.320
Will, you have a question?

00:55:45.320 --> 00:55:47.570
AUDIENCE: So when
we take omega goes

00:55:47.570 --> 00:55:49.820
to 0 from our previous
results, are we still justified

00:55:49.820 --> 00:55:52.320
in neglecting the
transient term?

00:55:56.820 --> 00:55:58.320
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:55:58.320 --> 00:55:59.136
But why?

00:56:12.260 --> 00:56:14.790
What will happen is
the transient term

00:56:14.790 --> 00:56:18.910
is really a term which
has time dependence.

00:56:18.910 --> 00:56:21.600
And even if omega is 0,
just the step function

00:56:21.600 --> 00:56:26.380
of switching it on
creates an oscillation

00:56:26.380 --> 00:56:30.790
in the atom at a frequency
which is omega excited

00:56:30.790 --> 00:56:33.240
state minus omega ground state.

00:56:33.240 --> 00:56:34.830
You may think
about it like this.

