01:09:39.609 --> 01:09:42.720
in a time dependent picture.

01:09:42.720 --> 01:09:45.140
So in other words, what
I'm telling you is there

01:09:45.140 --> 01:09:48.069
are two ways to obtain
the AC Stark shift.

01:09:48.069 --> 01:09:51.510
One is you do time dependent
perturbation theory assuming

01:09:51.510 --> 01:09:53.420
oscillating electric field.

01:09:53.420 --> 01:09:56.010
And that would mean in
the quantized language

01:09:56.010 --> 01:10:00.110
you assume the electromagnetic
field is in a coherent state.

01:10:00.110 --> 01:10:03.280
Alternatively, you can
quantize the electric field

01:10:03.280 --> 01:10:04.940
and introduce Fock states.

01:10:04.940 --> 01:10:10.470
And then because Fock
states are type independent,

01:10:10.470 --> 01:10:14.170
then these are the eigenstates
of the electromagnetic field

01:10:14.170 --> 01:10:15.360
in a cavity.

01:10:15.360 --> 01:10:18.324
And now you obtain the
same atomic level shift

01:10:18.324 --> 01:10:19.990
in time independent
perturbation theory.

01:10:29.070 --> 01:10:37.785
So in other words, we can
have photon number states.

01:10:40.570 --> 01:10:51.090
And do time independent
perturbation theory.

01:10:51.090 --> 01:10:57.160
Or alternatively, we can use a
semi-classical electric field.

01:10:59.680 --> 01:11:05.460
Which means we have a
classical electric field.

01:11:05.460 --> 01:11:09.399
And then we can treat
it in time dependent.

01:11:16.890 --> 01:11:22.330
All the textbooks generally
use the latter approach.

01:11:22.330 --> 01:11:25.390
Because it uses a same
classical electric field.

01:11:25.390 --> 01:11:29.960
But I can tell you, I strongly
prefer the first approach.

01:11:29.960 --> 01:11:31.625
Because in the
first approach, you

01:11:31.625 --> 01:11:33.520
have no problems whatsoever.

